To compute $\dbinom{16}{5}$, we will use the formula:

$$\dbinom{n}{r} = \frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}$$

First step: Calculate the factorial of 16. 

$$n! = 16! = 16 \times 15 \times 14 \times 13 \times 12 \times \cdots \times 3 \times 2 \times 1$$
Next step: Calculate the factorial of 5 and the factorial of 11 (since 16 - 5 = 11), then substitute these values into the formula.

$$r! = 5! = 5 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1$$
$$(n-r)! = 11! = 11 \times 10 \times 9 \times \cdots \times 3 \times 2 \times 1$$
Substitute the values of $n!$, $r!$, and $(n-r)!$ into the formula:

$$\dbinom{16}{5} = \frac{16!}{5!(16-5)!} = \frac{16!}{5!11!} = \frac{16 \times 15 \times 14 \times 13 \times 12 \times \cdots \times 3 \times 2 \times 1}{(5 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1)(11 \times 10 \times 9 \times \cdots \times 3 \times 2 \times 1)}$$

Now, cancel out the common factors in the numerator and denominator.

$$\dbinom{16}{5} = \frac{16 \times 15 \times 14 \times 13 \times 12}{5 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2  \times 1}$$

We can simplify this expression by evaluating the numerator and denominator.

Now, calculate the numerator:
$$16 \times 15 \times 14 \times 13 \times 12 = 524160$$ 
Then, calculate the denominator:
$$5 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1 = 120$$ 
Now, divide the numerator by the denominator:
$$\dbinom{16}{5} = \frac{524160}{120}$$
